author: JOHN ROWE
title: Local athletes in college: Oct. 21, 2015 - College Sports
text:
Kelly Wieczerzak, Wayne
Kelly Wieczerzak squeezed a season’s worth of highlights into a single game.
The sophomore from Wayne had not scored a collegiate goal going into Monmouth’s game against St. Peter’s last week, but she responded with the program’s first hat trick since 2012 in an 8-1 victory.
The former Wayne Valley star scored three consecutive goals for the Hawks, beginning with a penalty kick in the 40th minute. Her second goal two minutes later upped Monmouth’s lead to 6-0. Her final goal came in the 62nd minute.
Monmouth’s dominance was reflected in the final statistics. In registering their highest goal output of the season, the Hawks outshot St. Peter’s, 22-5, and had a 7-0 edge in corner-kick opportunities.
Justine Larocca, River Vale
* Justine Larocca of River Vale, who played at Pascack Valley, was among five women’s soccer players from The College of New Jersey recognized on Senior Night. The ninth-ranked Lions then earned a 2-1 win over Ramapo. 
Melissa Kelly, Parsippany
* Melissa Kelly, a sophomore from Parsippany and DePaul, scored three goals as Rowan routed William Paterson, 8-0. 
Sean Etheridge, Oakland
* Sean Etheridge, a junior from Oakland and Ramapo High School, contributed a goal as The College of New Jersey bested Ramapo, 4-2, in men’s soccer. It was Etheridge’s second goal of the season.
Grant Kelly, Wayne
* Rowan goalie Grant Kelly, a freshman from Wayne Hills, earned his first collegiate shutout by stopping six shots in the Profs’ 5-0 victory over Brooklyn. Angelica Giammetta, Wayne
* Angelica Giammetta, a senior from Wayne Hills, scored a goal as William Paterson’s field hockey team secured a spot in the MJAC tournament with a 3-2 victory over Stockton.
Danielle Havlicek, Midland Park, and Kendall Caruso, Secaucus
* Outside hitter Danielle Havlicek, a senior from Midland Park, had 16 kills and six digs in leading Rowan’s women’s volleyball team to its third straight conference victory, 3-0 over William Paterson. The Pioneers’ Kendall Caruso, a freshman from Secaucus, collected 22 assists and 10 digs.
Matt Tuohy, Oakland
* Matt Tuohy of Ramapo, a freshman from Oakland and Indian Hills, is the NJAC Cross-country Rookie of the Week after finishing 31st at the Inter-Regional Border Battle hosted by Rowan. His time was 25:31.5. Senior teammate Paul Juelis finished fifth in 24:57.4
Sydney Coughlin, Franklin Lakes
* Sydney Coughlin of St. Joseph’s, a junior from Franklin Lakes and Indian Hills, registered her squad’s second-best time (22:34) at the Princeton Invitational 6K, setting a meet record for a junior. As a freshman she ran 26:30, and as a sophomore she clocked 24:31.
Mike Shine, River Vale
